"gene", "prob": 0.995073139667511, "span": {"begin": 2607, "end": 2611}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6495"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "six1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9965314865112305, "span": {"begin": 2706, "end": 2710}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:10736"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "six2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9977401494979858, "span": {"begin": 2711, "end": 2715}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "progenitor fate", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8391469120979309, "span": {"begin": 2732, "end": 2747}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6495"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Six1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9966936111450195, "span": {"begin": 2854, "end": 2858}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "/Six2 genes", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.9058308601379395, "span": {"begin": 2858, "end": 2869}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:10736"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Six2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9982227087020874, "span": {"begin": 2859, "end": 2863}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human nephron progenitors", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.856555700302124, "span": {"begin": 2873, "end": 2898}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9755604267120361, "span": {"begin": 2873, "end": 2878}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10090"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mouse", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9869961738586426, "span": {"begin": 2922, "end": 2927}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6495"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Six1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9929897785186768, "span": {"begin": 2968, "end": 2972}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:10736"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "six2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9926280379295349, "span": {"begin": 3005, "end": 3009}}], "text": "Encouraging proliferation     Coletta et al., 2004 demonstrated a relationship between six1 overexpression and cyclin A1 mRNA levels and activity in multiple tissues.&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Six1 overexpression increases cyclin A1 mRNA levels and activity, cell proliferation, and tumor volume, whereas Six1 down-regulation decreases cyclin A1 mRNA levels and proliferation. Overexpression of Six1 in wild-type mouse embryonic fibroblasts, but not in knockout variants lacking the cyclin A1 gene, induces cell proliferation. Furthermore, inhibition of cyclin A1 in Six1-overexpressing mammary carcinoma cells decreases proliferation. Together these results demonstrate that cyclin A1 is required for the proliferative effect of Six1. We conclude that Six1 overexpression reinstates an embryonic pathway of proliferation in breast cancer by up-regulating cyclin A1.&rdquo;      Expanding progenitor population     Six1 expression has been shown to induce epithelia-to-mesenchymal transition (EMT), promoting self-renewal and stem-like behavior.&nbsp; Radisky 2009 is excrpted here.&nbsp;&ldquo;Isolated primary epithelial cells from Six1-expressing mice showed increased expression of the stem/progenitor cell&ndash;associated cell surface markers CD24 and CD29, as well as greatly increased growth as mammospheres, an assay that reflects cell self-renewal. Thus, Six1-induced EMT was associated with increases in the population of stem/progenitor cells and spontaneous tumor growth.&rdquo;   McCoy et al., 2009 concluded that&nbsp;&ldquo;Six1 may play a role in mammary epithelial stem cells, both in the normal gland as well as in tumorigenesis. Mammary epithelial cells from Six1-overexpressing mice are enriched for stem cells and have increased mammosphere-forming capability.&nbsp; Additionally, Six1-driven tumors contain cells of multiple mammary lineages and express Sca-1. Together, these data strongly suggest that Six1 promotes a stem cell phenotype in the normal mammary gland and that Six1-driven tumors arise from a stem/progenitor cell population.&rdquo;      Suppressing/altering differentiation     El-Hashash et al., 2011 found&nbsp;&ldquo;Six1 overexpression in MLE15 lung epithelial cells in vitro inhibited cell differentiation, but increases the expression of progenitor cell markers.&rdquo;   Suen et al., 2019 studied female mice exposed to diethylstilbestroL and found &ldquo;Abnormal endometrial glands express the oncofetal protein sine oculis homeobox 1 (SIX1) and contain cells with basal (cytokeratin [CK]14+/18-) and poorly differentiated features (CK14+/18+), strongly associating SIX1 with aberrant differentiation&hellip;&rdquo;      Stabilizing transcriptional feedback loops (six1/six2) that reinforce progenitor fate and self-renewal.     O&rsquo;Brien et al., 2016 highlights an auto/cross regulation relationship between Six1/Six2 genes in human nephron progenitors.&nbsp; However, in the mouse their relationship is independent, with Six1 expression occuring upstream of six2.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:56:37 +0000 2026"}